[It is unfortunate that the polio eradication effort has fallen victim to political and fundamentalist religious causes. The real victims in this travesty are the children in these areas who are being left behind in the war against polio. Between the violence perpetrated against vaccinators in Pakistan (and Nigeria) as part of religious movements and the campaigning against the vaccination efforts, the success of the polio eradication effort is being jeopardized. While the case count appears low at this point in time, the impact of reduced vaccination coverages may well start appearing as the number of susceptible children in the areas increases, permitting unstopped transmission of the wild poliovirus (WPV) as well as set the stage with ideal conditions for continued circulation of vaccine derived poliovirus (cVDPV).

In the past month since the last polio update, there has been an increase in the number of confirmed WPV associated cases from 2 cases to 11 cases. All 11 cases to date in 2013 have occurred in known polio endemic countries -- Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria.

On the positive note, the absence of WPV3 associated disease since the last confirmed case in April 2012 may well be heralding interruption of transmission of WPV3. If this continues, it will be the 2nd WPV type to have had its transmission interrupted worldwide -- the last reported case of WPV2 was in October 1999, in Alighar, Uttar Pradesh, India.

For a map of the locations of confirmed WPV associated polio cases see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx.

For a map of confirmed WPV associated polio cases by district of occurrence, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Polioinfecteddistricts.aspx. - Mod.MPP]
